$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
               Introduce the vector space axioms for a Hilbert space
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

  Here we introduce the axioms a complex Hilbert space, which is the foundation
  for quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.  The 18 axioms for a complex
  Hilbert space consist of ~ ax-hilex , ~ ax-hfvadd , ~ ax-hvcom , ~ ax-hvass ,
  ~ ax-hv0cl , ~ ax-hvaddid , ~ ax-hfvmul , ~ ax-hvmulid , ~ ax-hvmulass ,
  ~ ax-hvdistr1 , ~ ax-hvdistr2 , ~ ax-hvmul0 , ~ ax-hfi , ~ ax-his1 ,
  ~ ax-his2 , ~ ax-his3 , ~ ax-his4 , and ~ ax-hcompl .

  The axioms specify the properties of 5 primitive symbols, ` ~H ` , ` +h ` ,
  ` .h ` , ` 0h ` , and ` .ih ` .

  If we can prove in ZFC set theory that a class
  ` U = <. <. +h , .h >. , normh >. ` is a complex Hilbert space, i.e. that
  ` U e. CHilOLD ` , then these axioms can be proved as theorems ~ axhilex-zf ,
  ~ axhfvadd-zf , ~ axhvcom-zf , ~ axhvass-zf , ~ axhv0cl-zf , ~ axhvaddid-zf ,
  ~ axhfvmul-zf , ~ axhvmulid-zf , ~ axhvmulass-zf , ~ axhvdistr1-zf ,
  ~ axhvdistr2-zf , ~ axhvmul0-zf , ~ axhfi-zf , ~ axhis1-zf , ~ axhis2-zf ,
  ~ axhis3-zf , ~ axhis4-zf , and ~ axhcompl-zf respectively.  In that case,
  the theorems of the Hilbert Space Explorer will become theorems of ZFC set
  theory.  See also the comments in ~ axhilex-zf .

$)

  $( This is our first axiom for a complex Hilbert space, which is the
     foundation for quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.  We assume that
     there exists a primitive class, ` ~H ` , which contains objects called
     vectors.  (Contributed by NM, 16-Aug-1999.)
     (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hilex $a |- ~H e. _V $.

  $( Vector addition is an operation on ` ~H ` .  (Contributed by NM,
     16-Aug-1999.)  (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hfvadd $a |- +h : ( ~H X. ~H ) --> ~H $.

  $( Vector addition is commutative.  (Contributed by NM, 3-Sep-1999.)
     (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvcom $a |- ( ( A e. ~H /\ B e. ~H ) -> ( A +h B ) = ( B +h A ) ) $.

  $( Vector addition is associative.  (Contributed by NM, 3-Sep-1999.)
     (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvass $a |- ( ( A e. ~H /\ B e. ~H /\ C e. ~H ) ->
                 ( ( A +h B ) +h C ) = ( A +h ( B +h C ) ) ) $.

  $( The zero vector is in the vector space.  (Contributed by NM,
     29-May-1999.)  (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hv0cl $a |- 0h e. ~H $.

  $( Addition with the zero vector.  (Contributed by NM, 16-Aug-1999.)
     (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvaddid $a |- ( A e. ~H -> ( A +h 0h ) = A ) $.

  $( Scalar multiplication is an operation on ` CC ` and ` ~H ` .  (Contributed
     by NM, 16-Aug-1999.)  (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hfvmul $a |- .h : ( CC X. ~H ) --> ~H $.

  $( Scalar multiplication by one.  (Contributed by NM, 30-May-1999.)
     (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvmulid $a |- ( A e. ~H -> ( 1 .h A ) = A ) $.

  $( Scalar multiplication associative law.  (Contributed by NM, 30-May-1999.)
     (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvmulass $a |- ( ( A e. CC /\ B e. CC /\ C e. ~H ) ->
                 ( ( A x. B ) .h C ) = ( A .h ( B .h C ) ) ) $.

  $( Scalar multiplication distributive law.  (Contributed by NM, 3-Sep-1999.)
     (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvdistr1 $a |- ( ( A e. CC /\ B e. ~H /\ C e. ~H ) ->
                ( A .h ( B +h C ) ) = ( ( A .h B ) +h ( A .h C ) ) ) $.

  $( Scalar multiplication distributive law.  (Contributed by NM,
     30-May-1999.)  (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvdistr2 $a |- ( ( A e. CC /\ B e. CC /\ C e. ~H ) ->
                ( ( A + B ) .h C ) = ( ( A .h C ) +h ( B .h C ) ) ) $.

  $( Scalar multiplication by zero.  We can derive the existence of the
     negative of a vector from this axiom (see ~ hvsubid and ~ hvsubval ).
     (Contributed by NM, 29-May-1999.)  (New usage is discouraged.) $)
  ax-hvmul0 $a |- ( A e. ~H -> ( 0 .h A ) = 0h ) $.

